x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Reliance Playbook.</strong> Under=
take projects with high upfront costs, building complex businesses around t=
hem, wrangling Indian supply and demand, spreading out the costs over hundr=
eds of millions of users, leveraging its favorable position with the govern=
ment, and selling stakes to foreign companies and investors.&nbsp;</p></li>=
<li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p=
 style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><=
strong>Gateway of India. </strong>Foreign companies and investors poured $2=
0.4 billion into Jio for a 33% stake and are in the middle of investing in =
Reliance Retail, which has raised $5.1 billion for 8.5%.&nbsp;</p></li></ul=
><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 1em 0;">Reliance, which had raised billions of dollars in debt to fund it=
s new projects, now has zero net debt, strong relationships with the world&=
#8217;s largest investors, communications and retail infrastructure that po=
wers India, and the support of the Modi government, with whom it is working=
 to realize PM Modi&#8217;s mission of Atmanirbhar Bharat, a Self-Reliant I=
ndia that takes its place as a power on the global stage.&nbsp;</p><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
>In Part II of the essay, we&#8217;ll cover Reliance&#8217;s future and tha=
t of the Indian startup ecosystem, which will become increasingly intertwin=
ed:&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.7=
5px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Made by Reliance.</strong>=
 Reliance has always vertically integrated. Jio and Retail seem to be follo=
wing the same path, with homegrown and acquired solutions. That works bette=
r for infrastructure than it does for consumer apps.&nbsp;</p></li><li styl=
e=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong=
>The Indian Tech and Startup Ecosystem. </strong>The bull case for India te=
ch is that it is China, just seven or eight years behind, with better weste=
rn relations. Realizing the bull case would mean multiple hundred-billion d=
ollar tech companies and trillions of dollars of value creation. As it stan=
ds, Chinese investors will capture more Indian upside than Reliance.&nbsp;<=
/p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bul=
let;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0;"><strong>Reliance&#8217;s Tencent and SoftBank Opportunity. </strong>=
Reliance is well-positioned to become the next Asian mega-conglomerate turn=
ed investor. It can follow either Tencent&#8217;s or SoftBank&#8217;s appro=
ach, with a unique Indian spin.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #1a1a=
1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">To date, Relian=
ce has only built or acquired, while a thriving startup ecosystem has grown=
